<subSubSection pageId="69" pageNumber="70" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,639,290,1320]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,290,449,470]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named after the 
<typeStatus box="[151,192,476,497]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">type</typeStatus>
locality, Three Kings Islands.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="69" pageNumber="70" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,639,290,1320]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,280,502,523]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species can be distinguished from the other species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Broun" authorityYear="1911" box="[465,546,529,550]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Sagola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auripila">
<emphasis box="[465,546,529,550]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">auripila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
speciesgroup by the following combination of characters: larger body, length 
<quantity box="[348,427,582,603]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
; antennomere 1 with dull surface, 2–8 subquadrate; frontal sulcus deep, reaching vertexal fovea; gular region of male head depressed transversely; shape of genitalia unique to species; only known from Three Kings Islands.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="69" pageNumber="70" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,639,290,1320]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,386,715,736]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Description of Male.</emphasis>
Length 
<quantity box="[483,569,715,736]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
. Body brown, antennae, legs, maxillary palpi, and elytra paler (
<figureCitation box="[213,290,768,789]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[197,229,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[193,1176,940,1663]" captionTargetId="figure-360@64.[173,1193,920,1671]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 37. Habitus of Sagola species in the auripila species-group, dorsal views. a) S. auripila, b) S. spiniventris," figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907837/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Fig. 37f</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[315,376,768,789]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Head:</emphasis>
Round, widest across eyes (
<figureCitation box="[158,236,794,815]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[197,229,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[193,1176,940,1663]" captionTargetId="figure-360@64.[173,1193,920,1671]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 37. Habitus of Sagola species in the auripila species-group, dorsal views. a) S. auripila, b) S. spiniventris," figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907837/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Fig. 37f</figureCitation>
). Gular region of ventral surface of head depressed transversely. Antennomere 1 approximately 1.5 times longer than wide, with dull surface, 2–8 subquadrate, 9–10 weakly transverse. Frontal sulcus deep, reaching vertexal fovea from frontal rostrum. Anterior frontal fovea round and covered by frontal rostrum, posterior frontal fovea elongate. Eye small, approximately one-third length of temple. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[261,345,1007,1028]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Thorax:</emphasis>
Prosternum as long as wide, widest at midpoint. Elytra approximately triangular (
<figureCitation box="[159,238,1060,1081]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[197,229,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[193,1176,940,1663]" captionTargetId="figure-360@64.[173,1193,920,1671]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 37. Habitus of Sagola species in the auripila species-group, dorsal views. a) S. auripila, b) S. spiniventris," figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907837" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907837/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Fig. 37f</figureCitation>
). Meso- and metathorax trapezoidal, as long as wide. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[291,399,1087,1108]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Aedeagus:</emphasis>
Median lobe as long as paramere, with triangular apical lobe (
<figureCitation box="[538,619,1113,1134]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[175,207,1229,1248]" captionTargetBox="[156,1165,188,1205]" captionTargetId="figure-182@65.[151,1171,183,1212]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 38. Sagola species in the auripila species-group. Aedeagi, dorsal views: a) S. auripila, b) S. spiniventris, c) S. chathamensis, d) S. pittensis, e) S. chandleri, f) S. threekingsensis, g) S. gimmeli, h) S. sokolovi, lateral view, i) S. sokolovi. Dorsal surface of male head: j) S. spiniventris (arrow indicates wide frontal sulcus), k) S. chathamensis (arrow indicates narrow frontal sulcus). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907839" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907839/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Fig. 38f</figureCitation>
). Phallobase of median lobe symmetrical and rounded (
<figureCitation box="[159,237,1166,1187]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[175,207,1229,1248]" captionTargetBox="[156,1165,188,1205]" captionTargetId="figure-182@65.[151,1171,183,1212]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 38. Sagola species in the auripila species-group. Aedeagi, dorsal views: a) S. auripila, b) S. spiniventris, c) S. chathamensis, d) S. pittensis, e) S. chandleri, f) S. threekingsensis, g) S. gimmeli, h) S. sokolovi, lateral view, i) S. sokolovi. Dorsal surface of male head: j) S. spiniventris (arrow indicates wide frontal sulcus), k) S. chathamensis (arrow indicates narrow frontal sulcus). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907839" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907839/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Fig. 38f</figureCitation>
). Parameres asymmetrical, right weakly curved and divided, left rectangular (
<figureCitation box="[500,575,1193,1214]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="65.[175,207,1229,1248]" captionTargetBox="[156,1165,188,1205]" captionTargetId="figure-182@65.[151,1171,183,1212]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="Fig. 38. Sagola species in the auripila species-group. Aedeagi, dorsal views: a) S. auripila, b) S. spiniventris, c) S. chathamensis, d) S. pittensis, e) S. chandleri, f) S. threekingsensis, g) S. gimmeli, h) S. sokolovi, lateral view, i) S. sokolovi. Dorsal surface of male head: j) S. spiniventris (arrow indicates wide frontal sulcus), k) S. chathamensis (arrow indicates narrow frontal sulcus). Scale bars = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907839" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907839/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Fig. 38f</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="69" pageNumber="70" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,639,290,1320]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,306,1219,1240]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Distribution.</emphasis>
Three Kings Islands (
<figureCitation box="[553,634,1219,1240]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="68.[197,229,1638,1657]" captionTargetBox="[177,654,1079,1613]" captionTargetId="figure-619@68.[173,659,1076,1615]" captionTargetPageId="68" captionText="Fig. 40. Known collection localities of New Zealand Sagola species. S. pittensis: black circle; S. chandleri: triangles; S. threekingsensis: black square; S. gimmeli: star; S. sokolovi: white circles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4907843" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4907843/files/figure.png" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
: black square).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,639,290,1320]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,260,1273,1294]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Habitat.</emphasis>
Specimens of this species were collected by sifting leaf litter.
</paragraph>
